:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> comments on those provisions are attached herewith.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">We respond to a number of the general questions posed in the Call for Written Evidence as </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">follows</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q. 3</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Are the changes proposed in the draft Bill evidence-based and have any risks associated with the changes been taken adequately into account?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">A. 3</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">We are not convinced of the benefits/risk balance in the proposal to remove the obligation on a bankrupt to present a statement of affairs when the petition is presented by a creditor.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q. 4</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Does the draft Bill achieve its purpose of reducing the regulatory burden on business, organisations and individuals effectively and fairly?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">A. 4</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">On balance</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, yes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q. 5</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Will the draft Bill generally benefit businesses by offsetting other regulatory burdens?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">A. 5</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Reduction in administrative burdens in insolvency assignments will reduce costs. Consequently, more funds will be available for the creditors of the insolvent business.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q. 6</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">    To what extent does the draft Bill benefit consumers as well as businesses?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">A. 6 </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">   Amendments within Schedule 5 may benefit consumers who are creditors of insolvent</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">           </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">businesses</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">John Bowen-Walsh</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Secretary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Insolvency Committee</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">16</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:center; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">SCHEDULE 5, DRAFT DEREGULATION BILL</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:center; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">INSOLVENCY AND COMPANY LAW</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">DEEDS OF ARRANGEMENT</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">We agree that individual voluntary arrangements (“IVAs</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">”) have in practice replaced deeds of arrangement.  Accordingly, the Deeds of Arrangement Act 1914 is no longer required.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ADMINISTRATION OF COMPANIES</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">If a company has obtained the protection of an interim moratorium, which prevents other insolvency proceedings being commenced or continued against the company, it is appropriate that a company or its directors could appoint an administrator.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">If there are insufficient assets to make a distribution to unsecured creditors, they have no financial interest in the administration.  In such circumstances, approval of each secured creditor (and by at least 50% of the preferential creditors in value if they received/will receive a distribution) is sufficient to obtain release of the administrator.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">WINDING-UP OF COMPANIES  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">We agree that, following the introduction of statutory regulation of insolvency practitioners, Section 151, Insolvency Act 1986, has fallen into disuse and should be repealed. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The proposed Section 174(4) addresses a statutory anomaly.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">DISQUALIFICATION OF UNFIT DIRECTORS  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">It is appropriate to broaden the information gathering powers of the Secretary of State or the Official Receiver as proposed in the amendments to Schedule B1 to the Insolvency Act 1986.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">BANKRUPTCY</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">We are not convinced of the benefits/risk balance in the proposal to remove the obligation on a bankrupt to present a statement of affairs when the petition is presented by a creditor.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">It is preferable that, where the trustee in bankruptcy is considering making a claim against the bank for after-acquired property, he/she should serve notice on the bank regarding that property. It is hoped this statutory revision  will incentivise the bank to provide an account for the undischarged bankrupt.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">We agree that the Court should have the choice of appointing either the Official Receiver or a private sector insolvency practitioner where it is deemed necessary to have an interim receiver to preserve a debtor’s assets.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">AUTHORISATION OF INSOLVENCY PRACTITIONERS</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">We agree that, as a consequence ofo other proposed statutory changes, Sections 389(1A) and 389A, Insolvency Act 1986, will become obsolete.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">LIABILITIES OF ADMINISTRATIORS AND ADMINISTRATIVE RECEIVERS</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">We concur with the removal of the specific subsections/paragraphs in the Insolvency Act 1986 addressing “year-in-hand schemes”, following prohibition of su</span><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">h schemes by the Working Time Regulations 1998.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">REQUIREMENT OF COMPANY LAW</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">We concur with the changes proposed to Sections 327(2) and 330(6), Companies Act, 2006. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>